      "publication_year": 1987,
      "publication_date": "1987-10-01",
      "abstract": "Both terms of my topic may not generally be held in clear focus. I will therefore begin with names of some of those I take to be, by their main accents, representative of each of two perspectives. Civilization analysis stands for Max Weber, Norbert Elias, Louis Dumont, Benjamin Nelson, S. N. Eisenstadt. History of consciousness is represented by Michel Foucault, Philippe Aries, Hayden White, Fredric Jameson, H. D. Harootunian. The second list could be greatly expanded: it points to a currently fashionable approach. Most of those listed (to their own credit) are not pure representatives of one of these perspectives. Foucault in his substantive works on madness, clinicalization of medicine, and imprisonment is almost as much a civilization analyst as historian of consciousness. Among those who can be identified with civilizational approach, Elias (in his studies of the civilizing process) is closest to history of consciousness, Eisenstadt wholly alien to it. Shifts occur over time. Dumont in his later work on European political philosophy has moved toward history of consciousness, as have several others. Any movement in opposite direction is barely perceptible. I have chosen to compare these two scientific programs because, first, both are important to civilizational studies, capable of grasping what is essential to civilizations as distinguished from other entities, and second, both are more than merely technical disciplines, rather constituting broad intellectual and human orientations. It is not possible to be a cultured person, in sense in which nineteenth-century east Europeans used term, without having become deeply engaged with both history of consciousness and civilization analysis. I will focus on two tendencies both of which may exist in same author, but which carry him or her in different directions. I will touch upon their logics, phenomenologies, points of contact, and critical evaluations.",
